il scientists, agronomists, archaeologists, historians, and engineers and told how the applications of their work produced an agricultural surplus in this forbiddingly dry, hot region. , Now Michael Evenari has amplified the book with data from another decade of work. He describes the efforts at a new farm at Wadi Mashash, extends the weather data another ten years, presents further work on the adaptations of plants and animals to desert conditions, and takes a much deeper look at the historical precedents for the method of runoff agriculture, which has made the desert bloom.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aArid regions agriculture. 0aDesert ecology. 0aHydrology. 0aWirtschaft. 4aAgriculture -- Israel -- Negev. 4aArid regions agriculture -- Israel -- Negev. 4aHydrology -- Israel -- Negev. 4aPhysical geography -- Israel -- Negev. 4aSCIENCE / Life Sciences / Botany. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aItzhaki, Yehoshua, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShanan, Leslie, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aShkolnik, Amiram, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTadmor, Naphtali, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP e-dition: Complete eBook Packagez9783110353488oZDB-23-HCO08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP e-dition: Science eBook Packagez9783110353549oZDB-23-HSP08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook Package Archive 1893-1999z97831104422120 cprintz978067441924740uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/harvard.978067441925440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674419254423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674419254/original  a978-3-11-044221-2  HUP eBook Package 